Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Kenya Power & Lighting, Union Bank

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-06-23T16:18:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-23/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-power-lighting-union-bank.html
    The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index advanced for a second day, adding 0.5 percent to
25,185.27 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according an e-mailed
statement from the exchange.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  slumped 1.6 percent to
801.43 by the 4 p.m. close in  Windhoek . Kenya’s All-Share Index
declined for a second day, falling 0.1 percent to 70.10 by the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi, the lowest close since April 2010.
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index retreated 0.3 percent to 2,085.21 by
the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index declined for a second day , erasing 0.1 percent
to 1,185.75 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.          The following
shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa , excluding  South
Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Power & Lighting Ltd. (KPLL)  , the East African
nation’s sole electricity distributor, climbed 0.25 cents, or
1.2 percent, to 21.75 shillings, heading for the strongest close
since May 23, after the Nairobi-based company said it expects to
increase sales by 7 percent to 6,020 gigawatt hours this year.  Union Bank of Nigeria Plc (UBN NL), a lender bailed out by
the nation’s central bank in 2009, jumped 11 kobo, or 5 percent,
to 2.31 naira, the highest level since June 3, after Chief
Executive Officer Funke Osibodu said the bank plans to conclude
recapitalization in September after reaching a deal with
investors.  To contact the reporter on this story:
